===Stereotype lift and stereotype boost===
Stereotype threat concerns how stereotypes harm performance; however stereotype activation can also lead to performance enhancement in certain situations. An increase in performance can arise due to stereotype lift which occurs when people are exposed to negative stereotypes about another group.<ref name="Walton 2003 456–467">{{cite journal|last=Walton|first=G. M.|coauthors=Cohen, G. L.|title=Stereotype lift|journal=Journal of Experimental Social Psychology|year=2003|volume=39|issue=5|pages=456–467|doi=10.1016/S0022-1031(03)00019-2}}</ref> This enhanced performance has been attributed to increases in [[self-efficacy|self-efficacy]] and decreases in self-doubt as a result of negative [[Ingroups_and_outgroups|outgroup]] stereotypes.<ref name="Walton 2003 456–467"/> Another situation which can lead to performance enhancement is when stereotype boost occurs. Stereotype boost theorists posit that positive stereotypes may actually enhance performance.<ref name="Shih, M. J. 2012 141–156">{{cite book|title=Stereotype Threat: Theory, Process, and Application|year=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0199732442|pages=141–156|author=Shih, M. J.|coauthors=Pittinsky, T.L.; Ho, G. C.|editor=Inzlicht, M.; Schmader, T.|chapter=Stereotype boost: Positive outcomes from the activation of positive stereotypes}}</ref> Stereotype boost occurs when a positive aspect of an individual's social identity is made salient in an identity relevant domain. Consistent with the positive racial stereotype concerning their superior quantitative skills, [[Asian_American|Asian American]] women performed better on a math test when their Asian identity was [[Priming_(psychology)|primed]] compared to a [[Treatment_and_control_groups|control condition]] where no social identity was primed. Conversely, participants did worse on the math test when their gender identity was made salient which is consistent with stereotype threat.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Shih|first=M|coauthors=Pittinsky, T.L.; Trahan, A.|title=Domain-specific effects of stereotypes on performance|journal=Self and Identity|year=2006|volume=5|issue=1|pages=1–14|doi=10.1080/15298860500338534|url=https://research.hks.harvard.edu/publications/getFile.aspx?Id=171}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Steen|first=L. A.|title=Mathematics education: A predictor of scientific competitiveness|journal=Science|date=17 July 1987|volume=237|issue=4812|pages=251–302|doi=10.1126/science.237.4812.251|url=http://www.stolaf.edu/people/steen/Papers/87predict.pdf|author=|access-date=2013-09-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203040055/http://www.stolaf.edu/people/steen/Papers/87predict.pdf|archive-date=2013-12-03|dead-url=yes}}</ref> Although stereotype boost is similar to stereotype lift in that they both result in a performance enhancement due to stereotype activation, stereotype lift is the result of a negative outgroup stereotype while stereotype boost occurs due to activation of a positive [[Ingroups_and_outgroups|ingroup]] stereotype.<ref name="Shih, M. J. 2012 141–156"/>
